  "text": "Salmonella can utilize ferric iron via FepB as its sole iron source. Next, we determined whether ferric iron is sufficient to support Salmonella growth in broth. Control experiments demonstrated no significant growth differences between the ⌬fepB mutant and the wild-type strain in nutrient-rich medium (LB medium) at 37°C over 16 h (Fig. 3A) . The addition of the iron chelator 2,2=-dipyridyl, which has a similar binding affinity for ferrous and ferric iron [CITATION_1] , prevented the growth of both strains similarly. In M9 minimal medium without added iron, the wild-type strain grew significantly better than the ⌬fepB mutant strain (Fig.  3B) . Treatment with 100 but not 50 M ferric chloride significantly increased growth of the wild-type strain. Growth of the ⌬fepB mutant strain was not improved by the addition of ferric chloride. Chelation of iron with 2,2=-dipyridyl in M9 medium reduced the growth of both wild-type Salmonella and the ⌬fepB strain, as observed in LB medium. Collectively, these observations suggest that Salmonella can utilize ferric iron acquired via the catecholate transporter FepB as its sole iron source.",
